ost/aus-newcastle/archives/255',0,'revision','',0),(256,1,'2012-10-12 12:47:10','2012-10-12 03:47:10','<a href=\"http://localhost/aus-newcastle/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/convict-lumber-yard.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-267\" title=\"convict lumber yard\" src=\"http://localhost/aus-newcastle/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/convict-lumber-yard.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"684\" height=\"456\" /></a>The <strong>Convict Lumberyard</strong> and <strong>Stockade</strong> is considered to be of National heritage significance. It contains information relating to the second oldest city outside Sydney in Australia. You can find information relating to the economic and industrial growth of nation.\r\nThis popular place was once a convict industrial workplace until about 1850. The place summarizes the key reasons for the establishment of Newcastle. It keeps important proofs of Aboriginal life ways prior to 1804. Managed by the NSW City Council, the lumberyard and stockade holds archaeological evidence and industrial heritage. You can get to have a glimpse into the harsh days of penal settlement.\r\n\r\nThe lumberyard and stockade has the markings of the beginnings of industry in Newcastle, and it is also Australia’s first convict work site. There’s a potential for you to find information about colonial and convict life in Australia in this place. The lumberyard and stockade was also where convicts lived before. Now, much of the fabric form from the era of convicts remains buried beneath the sand drifts that covered the site. You can locate this site near the Newcastle Railway Station at 92 Scott Street.','Convict Lumberyard and Stockade','','publish','open','open','','convict-lumberyard-and-stockade','','','2012-10-12 13:53:57','2012-10-12 04:53:57','',102,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/?page_id=256',0,'page','',0),(257,1,'2012-10-12 12:45:48','2012-10-12 03:45:48','The Convict Lumberyard and Stockade is considered to be of National heritage significance. It contain