'','inherit','open','open','','293-autosave','','','2012-10-12 14:42:32','2012-10-12 05:42:32','',293,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/archives/298',0,'revision','',0),(299,1,'2012-10-12 14:45:51','2012-10-12 05:45:51','<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a href=\"http://localhost/aus-newcastle/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/fortscratchley.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-306 alignright\" title=\"fortscratchley\" src=\"http://localhost/aus-newcastle/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/fortscratchley.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"312\" height=\"183\" /></a>Explore the underground tunnels of the Fort Scratchley Historic Site and wonder at the oldest working guns in Australia. Fort Scratchley was built between 1881 and 886, and designed by Lt Col. Peter Scratchley. The site is a national historic landmark, overlooking the Nobbys beach. Fort Scratchley is rich in military history. It certainly is an icon of the Newcastle and the Hunter Valley Region.</p>\r\nTake a stroll around the site, immerse yourself in history, and experience the breathtaking views in your self guided tours around the barracks and above the ground defense structures. The general admission is free. There are self guided brochures available from the Artillery Store to assist you in navigating the site and learning interesting historical facts. The site is open 6 days a week, from 10am to 4pm, and is closed on Tuesdays.\r\n\r\nYou can also enjoy picnic lunch and other recreational activities on the grounds. The site is also has a great position for whale watching. Binoculars are available for hire from the Artillery Store. From the site, it is an easy walk to the heart of the Newcastle City Centre. Fort Scratchley is also the home to the Newcastle Maritime Centre.\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>TOURS AND VISITOR INFORMATION</strong>\r\n<strong>Address:</strong>\r\nNobbys Road, Newcastle East, NSW 2300\r\n<strong>Phone:</strong> +61 2 4974 5033\r\n<strong>Fax:</strong> + 61 2 4974 2172\r\n<strong>Email:</strong> <a hre