\n\r\nCivic Precinct is easily accessible by road, rail, air or water. Over 700 accommodation rooms can be found just 5 minutes walk from the precinct. It is also a short walk from Newcastle’s major attractions, beaches, harbor foreshore, cafes and restaurants. In this precinct, there are four unique flexible venues: Civic Theatre, City Hall, Wheeler Place, and the Playhouse.\r\n\r\nEnjoy events at the Civic theatre, one of Australia’s great historic theatres, which hosts a wide range of concerts, musicals, plays, dance, and other events. It has an art deco Style of the 1920’s which supports 1520 seats. It is one of Newcastle’s most popular and prestigious venues and offers several function rooms aside from the main auditorium.\r\n\r\nAdmire the City Hall, opened in 1929 and extensively renovated in 2001, which is now a conference and function centre. The City hall is one of the Hunter Region’s largest and most prestigious venues, having 7 functions &amp; conference rooms. It is designed on the Spanish Baroque Style of architect Henry Eli White, which is proud of its architecture and ambience. City Hall caters wedding receptions, and it is also a stunning place for photographs where its balcony is overlooking Civic Park.\r\n\r\nVisit the Wheeler Place, a unique event destination which is ideal for exhibitions, conference options, product launches, and all forms of entertainment. The Wheeler Place is a 1200m² open air space, neighboring to the City Hall to the south. It compromises of three discreet areas: South Wheeler Place, Undercoft, North Wheeler Place.\r\n\r\nTake a look at the Playhouse, designed by local architect Brian Suters. It has been refurbished with 205 seats. Its first incarnation opened in 1979, and it is now the new home for performing arts.','Civic Cultural Precinct','','publish','open','closed','','civic-cultural-precinct','','','2012-10-12 16:12:51','2012-10-12 07:12:51','',311,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/?page_id=321',0,'page','',0),(322,1,'