hings To Do','','publish','open','closed','','free-things-to-do','','','2012-10-13 23:56:50','2012-10-13 14:56:50','',34,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/?page_id=432',0,'page','',0),(433,1,'2012-10-13 23:46:16','2012-10-13 14:46:16','','Free','','inherit','open','open','','432-revision','','','2012-10-13 23:46:16','2012-10-13 14:46:16','',432,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/archives/433',0,'revision','',0),(435,1,'2012-10-13 23:47:56','2012-10-13 14:47:56','Purse strings have been tightening all over, but it doesn’t mean you have to stay at home! If you want to get out of the house but you’re feeling the pinch, don’t fret for there are a lot of activities and events going on around Newcastle and the Hunter Region that are free. Check them out with no cost to you and save your change for your next beverage!\r\n\r\nIf you like to surf, visit the cities of Newcastle and Lake Macquarie including the councils of Port Stephens and Great Lakes. In the City of Newcastle, there are a lot of free beaches and ocean baths for you to swim at for free! Furthermore, Newcastle is home to Merewether Beach where the biggest surf festival in Australia, the Surfest Festival, is held annually.\r\n\r\nNewcastle is one of those places that are so fun to discover. There are lots to see outside the main cities. Look for many attractions including the historical and cultural self guided tours, art galleries, museums and shows and especially exploring nature!','Newcastle & Hunter Region','','publish','closed','closed','','free-things-to-do-in-newcastle-hunter-region','','','2012-10-14 01:19:50','2012-10-13 16:19:50','',432,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/?page_id=435',0,'page','',0),(436,1,'2012-10-13 23:47:30','2012-10-13 14:47:30','','Free Things to do  in Newcastle & Hunter Region','','inherit','open','open','','435-revision','','','2012-10-13 23:47:30','2012-10-13 14:47:30','',435,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/archives/436',0,'revision','',0),(437,1,'2012-10-13 23:53:26','2012-10-13 14:53:26','Go for the <strong>Hunter Valley Wine Tastings</strong> at Hungerford Hill or Poole\'s Rock in Pokolbin for free wine tastings. Most of the vineyards in the Hunter Valley offer free wine tasting for you to enjoy.\r\n\r\nListen to the <strong>Live Music at the Brewery</strong> for free, including DJ’s, every Wednesday, Friday, Saturday and Sunday.\r\n\r\nAdmission to the <strong>Hunter Region Botanic Gardens</strong> is free for individuals. The Gardens are located on the Pacific Highway, 4km north of the Hexham Bridge between Newcastle and Raymond Terrace.  The gardens are an ideal venue for educational excursions and tour group.  For more information <a href=\"http://www.huntergardens.org.au\" target=\"_blank\">click here</a>\r\n\r\nDiscover the <a href=\"http://www.visitnsw.com/destinations/hunter/hunter-valley/cessnock/attractions/werakata-national-park\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Werakata National Park</strong></a> in Cessnock which offers bushwalking, mountain bike riding and picnicking. Walk around <strong>Watagans National Park</strong> and cool off on a hot day at the many creeks in the park.\r\n\r\nVisit <a href=\"http://crag.net.au/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Cessnock Regional Art Gallery</strong></a> at <a href=\"http://www.thehunterblackboard.com/galleries\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Cessnock for exhibitions</strong></a> showcasing the work of artists from the Hunter Region, incoming touring shows and artist survey exhibitions that cover the contemporary visual arts, craft and design, including historical and contemporary themes and subjects. Entrance to the gallery is free.\r\n\r\nExplore the award-winning <a href=\"http://artgallery.lakemac.com.au/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Lake Macquarie City Art Gallery</strong></a> with state-of-the-art seminar facilities a sculpture park, mosaic pathways, and the historic Awaba House Restaurant Cafe. Unique and widely recognised for its exhibition program and work with the community, Lake Macquarie City Art Gallery is an exceptional cultural and tourist destination. Furthermore, the admission entry is free!\r\n\r\nYou can also visit <a href=\"http://mrag.org.au/education/self-guided-free/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Maitland Regional Art Gallery</strong></a> in Maitland for free of charge.\r\n\r\nFor coastal walks, go to the coastal cities and councils of the Hunter Region. Walk along the coasts of the Great Lakes, Port Stephens, Newcastle and Lake Macquarie and discover the shipwrecks that you may find in certain locations along the coast.\r\n\r\nFamous for its convict history, the Hunter Region offers you the Convict Trail to which you could walk for free discovering and learning about the convict history of the region.\r\n\r\nIf you are more of a cycle enthusiast, you can cycle for free on the trails. For cycle ways in the Hunter Region, visit <strong><a href=\"http://www.bicycleinfo.nsw.gov.au/maps/cycleways.html\" target=\"_blank\">Cycle Way Finder</a></strong> from Bicycle Information for New South Wales\r\n\r\nYou can watch dolphins and whale from a number of locations in the coastal cities and councils of the Hunter Region without spending a dime! For these spots, check out <em><strong>Whale Watching in Newcastle and Hunter Region<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">.</span></strong></em>\r\n\r\nRecreational fishing is a popular activity in the Hunter Region. You can actually fish without spending a penny as long as you already purchased a fishing license and the fishing equipments. For more information on fishing in the Hunter Region, check out <em><strong>Fishing in Newcastle and Hunter Region</strong></em>.\r\n\r\nYou can spend time with the whole family for a picnic in the parks in Hunter Region.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Free Things to do in Hunter Region','','publish','closed','closed','','free-things-to-do-in-hunter-region','','','2012-10-14 01:14:14','2012-10-13 16:14:14','',435,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/?page_id=437',0,'page','',0),(438,1,'2012-