y won’t disappoint you. Furthermore, since Newcastle is situated within the Hunter Region, the Hunter Valley wineries and the Hunter Valley Botanic Gardens are only minutes away.\r\n\r\nWhatever form of entertainment or adventure you\'re searching for, you won\'t be disappointed with this port city. Explore the destinations below and enjoy what Newcastle can offer you!','Destination','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-11','','','2012-10-09 19:01:19','2012-10-09 10:01:19','',102,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/archives/486',0,'revision','',0),(487,1,'2012-10-15 19:17:08','2012-10-15 10:17:08','Newcastle has everything that you are looking for.\r\n\r\nNewcastle has a land area of 261.8 km² on the Hunter Region. Lying on the New South Wales coast at the mouth of the Hunter River, Newcastle offers the best beaches and ocean baths in NSW for you to relax, to surf in, and take pleasure in.\r\n\r\nRich with unique history, the city is full of prestigious venues and landmarks. From the mix of boutique shopping, inner city galleries, lively night life, excellent dining, to breathtaking sightseeing of the harbor, this city won’t disappoint you. Furthermore, since Newcastle is situated within the Hunter Region, the Hunter Valley wineries and the Hunter Valley Botanic Gardens are only minutes away.\r\n\r\nWhatever form of entertainment or adventure you\'re searching for, you won\'t be disappointed with this port city. Explore the destinations below and enjoy what Newcastle can offer you!','Destination','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-12','','','2012-10-15 19:17:08','2012-10-15 10:17:08','',102,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/archives/487',0,'revision','',0),(488,1,'2012-10-16 16:11:06','2012-10-16 07:11:06','<strong>Having a population of 645,395, Hunter Region is the sixth largest metropolitan region in New South Wales. 80% of the population lives in Lower Hunter or the Metropolitan Area of Newcastle.</strong>\r\n\r\nThe Hunter Region has emerged from a largely industrial, coal and wine producing past to become the diverse industrial base, making the region an important contributor to the economy of New South Wales. Home to one of Australia’s most dynamic communities, the region was able to capitalize its wealth of natural resources helped by hard work. Furthermore, the Hunter Region is willing to adapt itself to the demands of Australia’s increasingly diversified economy.\r\n\r\nThe huge coal reserves have been the foundation of the Hunter’s economic growth making it one of the region’s greatest assets. With the low cost coal, the region became one of NSW’s major electricity generating areas.\r\n\r\nAside from the coal exports, having a long history of manufacturing mainly in general engineering and ship building, the Hunter Region is also successful in exporting manufactured products throughout the world.\r\n\r\nKnowledge-based industries aren’t second to other industries in the Hunter Region. Courses that meet modern business and industry needs are being designed by universities such as the University of Newcastle and the Hunter TAFE with the cooperation of regional employers.\r\n\r\nThere has been a continuing growth trend with the number of people employed since 1996 to 2006, rising from 220, 000 to 286,000. The unemployment rate of the Hunter Region is lower compared to the average of the state. Hunter Region has an enhanced availability of labour because of the excellent road, rail and public transport network, giving the workers easy access.','Living in Hunter Region','','publish','closed','closed','','living-in-newcastle','','','2012-10-16 16:44:21','2012-10-16 07:44:21','',37,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/?page_id=488',0,'page','',0),(489,1,'2012-10-16 16:11:03','2012-10-16 07:11:03','Having a population of 645,395, Hunter Region is the sixth largest metropolitan region in New South Wales. 80% of the population lives in Lower Hunter or the Metropolitan Area of Newcastle.\n\nThe Hunter Region has emerged f