'revision','',0),(545,1,'2012-10-16 17:31:34','2012-10-16 08:31:34','In Australia, people are free to practice and follow their own beliefs and religion. Cultural and religious diversity is an important part of life in Australia. You will find many churches, temples, synagogues, mosques and other places of worship in Sydney and in other cities and towns in NSW.\r\n\r\nAccording to the Population Census in 2006, there are approximately 74% of the residents in the Hunter Region who identified Christianity as their personal religion. In the Hunter Region, the most common religion in Christianity were the Anglican, Catholic, Uniting Church and Presbyterian and Reformed faiths.\r\n\r\nOver the ten years to 2006, approximately from 12% to 15% of the amount of Hunter residents who reported having no religion rose. Though the trend applies to all age groups, it is most obvious among the younger people.\r\n\r\nThe City of Newcastle is home to both the Anglican and Catholic Dioceses in the Hunter Region.','Religion','','inherit','open','closed','','541-revision-2','','','2012-10-16 17:31:34','2012-10-16 08:31:34','',541,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/archives/545',0,'revision','',0),(546,1,'2012-10-16 17:37:31','2012-10-16 08:37:31','In Australia, people are free to practice and follow their own beliefs and religion. Cultural and religious diversity is an important part of life in Australia. You will find many churches, temples, synagogues, mosques and other places of worship in Sydney and in other cities and towns in NSW.\r\n\r\nAccording to the Population Census in 2006, there are approximately 74% of the residents in the Hunter Region who identified Christianity as their personal religion. In the Hunter Region, the most common religion in Christianity were the Anglican, Catholic, Uniting Church and Presbyterian and Reformed faiths.\r\n\r\nOver the ten years to 2006, approximately from 12% to 15% of the amount of Hunter residents who reported having no religion rose. Thoug