ll levels which compete across the region. The sports include cricket, soccer, netball, basketball, rugby league, rugby union, AFL and hockey. Recreational and racing types of sailing are also being enjoyed in the region on all the waterways.\r\n<h3>Newcastle Sports</h3>\r\nNewcastle has a strong sporting culture. There is a number of international, national and local training and sporting facilities for plenty of sports including cricket, horse racing, ice hockey and skating, baseball, netball, rugby league and other various sports. You’ll also find cycle ways, ovals and parks for sporting enthusiasts.\r\n\r\nJunior National games were also hosted in Newcastle frequently.  Recently, it was told on the news that Newcastle will host the inaugural Special Olympics Asia Pacific Regional Games in 2013.\r\n<h3>Newcastle &amp; Hunter Region Sporting Venues</h3>\r\n<h4>Cessnock Sportsground</h4>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Constructed in 2004, Cessnock Sportsground is a state of the art sporting venue that can cater for a broad array of evens all year round. The sportsground is the showcase regional sporting and community venue of Cessnock and it is only ten minutes away from Cessnock business district. As part of the Baddeley Park Complex, its former name was Baddeley Park able to accommodate seats for 1400 spectators. The grand stand is fully accessible and caters for patrons with disabilities. There’s also a small function room with an open view of the field with the capacity for 20 people.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>Address: </strong>Vincent Street Cessnock, NSW 2325\r\n<strong>Phone:</strong> 0421703570</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Hunter Sports Centre</h4>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Opened on the 13<sup>th</sup> of February 1999, the Hunter Sports Centre is one of the premier sporting venues in the Australian State of New South Wales. The venue operates 7 days a week; close during the public holidays. It is located 10 km south west of Newcastle and approximately 120 km north of Sydney.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>Address:</strong>43 Stockland Drive, Glendale, NSW 2285\r\n<strong>Phone:</strong> 02 4953 6366\r\n<strong>Fax:</strong> 02 4953 6587\r\n<strong>Email:</strong> <a href=\"mailto:info@hsc.org.au\">info@hsc.org.au</a>\r\n<strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"http://hsc.org.au\" target=\"_blank\">hsc.org.au</a></p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Hunter Stadium</h4>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Previously known as Ausgrid Stadium, the Hunter Stadium was originally known as the International Sports Centre. It is a rectangular multi-purpose outdoor stadium that had been the home ground to the Newcastle Knights and Newcastle Jets. Hunter stadium has a capacity 30,000. The stadium is now competing on an international level.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>Address:</strong> Turton Road, Lambton\r\n<strong>Website:</strong> <a href=\"http://hunterstadium.com.au\" target=\"_blank\">hunterstadium.com.au</a></p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Newcastle Entertainment Centre</h4>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The Newcastle Entertainment Centre is one of Australia\'s most flexible multi-purpose venues. It was officially opened in June 1992. The centre offers 5,000 square metres of clear span floor space. It is capable of catering for capacities from 2,000 to 6,500 for entertainment style events. There are variety of shows held in the centre, including rock and popular concerts, circuses, ice shows, school spectaculars, basketball, tennis, boxing, gymnastics, indoor motocross, exhibitions, conventions and functions.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>Address: </strong>Showground Brown Rd., Broadmeadow\r\n<strong>Phone:</strong> 02 4921 2100</p>\r\n\r\n<h4> Newcastle No.1 Sportsground</h4>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Located a short walk from the CBD, No.1 Sportsground is a multi-use stadium currently used for Australian Rules Football, cricket and Rugby League though normally used for cricket matches. The sports ground has a capacity of 20,000. It hosted 3 Australian domestic fixtures including Pupa Cup games. Aside from that, the sports ground host the local Rugby League and AFL grand finals each year.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Port Macquarie Regional Stadium</h4>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Constructed in 1992 with funding assistance from NSW Sport &amp; Recreation, NSW Country Rugby League and Hastings Council, Port Macquarie Regional Stadium became a primary location of rugby league in the North Coast region. The venue was transformed from a playing field to a genuine high quality sports stadium as it has been constructed recently with a 1,000 seat grandstand. Although rugby league is the predominant sport played at the stadium, rugby union and soccer fixtures.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>Address:</strong> Port Macquarie, NSW</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>The Gardens Greyhound Sporting Complex</h4>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">There has been a major transformation from Newcastle’s second largest rectangular stadium into the city’s main Greyhound venue which was completed in 2OO5. Previously known as Breakers Stadium and also Topper Stadium, the Gardens has the total capacity of around 2,000 including 1,100 seats of the venue is Greyhound Racing (held each Friday &amp; Wednesday night), the in-field can also host Rugby League, Rugby Union and Soccer.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>Address: </strong>104 Sandgate Road, Birmingham Gardens</p>','Sports','','publish','closed','closed','','sports','','','2012-10-20 03:46:18','2012-10-19 18:46:18','',37,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/?page_id=612',6,'page','',0),(613,1,'2012-10-20 03:10:13','2012-10-19 18:10:13','','Sports','','inherit','open','closed','','612-revision','','','2012-10-20 03:10:13','2012-10-19 18:10:13','',612,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/archives/613',0,'revision','',0),(614,1,'2012-10-20 03:11:18','2012-10-19 18:11:18',' ','','','publish','open','close