t was abandoned after convict mutiny. Hunter exported its first cedar cut. The second attempt at penal colony was successful in 1804. In 1818, the breakwater to join Nobbys island to the shore was started, ordered by Governr Macquarie to create the port.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nDisastrous Hunter floods came in 1819. By 1822, most of the convicts held at Newcastle were transferred to Port Macqaurie. In 1826, the coal mining was taken from the Government by the A.A. Company. The Great North Road was completed by 1828. The town of Maitland and the village of Wollombi were proclaimed in 1833 followed by the proclamation of the town of Scone in 1837. Australia’s first steamship company was formed in 1838. By 1840, the town of Dungog was established.\r\n\r\nThe first edition of Maitland Mercury, along with the Newcastle District Council, was established by 1843. In 1845, the first dredging of the Hunter River estuary happened. Ferry service between Stockton and Newcastle begun and Nobbys Breakwater completed in 1846. A year after Newcastle was proclaimed as a city. Newcastle Harbour was dredged for the first time during 1858. By 1859, Newcastle was declared as a municipality. The rail link from Newcastle reached Singleton in 1863. Five years after, an earthquake shook Newcastle and Maitland.\r\n\r\nThe railway line was extended from Newcastle to Tamworth in 1878. By 1887, the governor of NSW opened the stream tram line, linking Newcastle and Wallsend / Plattsburg. In 1888, the city of Newcastle was linked to Brisbane by rail. Sydney-Newcastle rail line was completed in 1889. Hunter was visited by devastating floods in 1893. Lake Macquarie was proclaimed as a Shire in 1906 following the proclamation of the village of Cessnock in 1908. By 1944, Maitland became a municipality but experienced severe flooding in 1949.\r\n\r\nElectric trams were eliminated from Newcastle city and suburbs by 1950. By 1952, the Hexham Bridge opened. Queen Elizabeth II and the Duke of Edinburgh visited 