 successful in 1804. In 1818, the breakwater to join Nobbys island to the shore was started, ordered by Governr Macquarie to create the port.\r\n\r\nDisastrous Hunter floods came in 1819. By 1822, most of the convicts held at Newcastle were transferred to Port Macqaurie. In 1826, the coal mining was taken from the Government by the A.A. Company. The Great North Road was completed by 1828. The town of Maitland and the village of Wollombi were proclaimed in 1833 followed by the proclamation of the town of Scone in 1837. Australia’s first steamship company was formed in 1838. By 1840, the town of Dungog was established.\r\n\r\nThe first edition of Maitland Mercury, along with the Newcastle District Council, was established by 1843. In 1845, the first dredging of the Hunter River estuary happened. Ferry service between Stockton and Newcastle begun and Nobbys Breakwater completed in 1846. A year after Newcastle was proclaimed as a city. Newcastle Harbour was dredged for the first time during 1858. By 1859, Newcastle was declared as a municipality. The rail link from Newcastle reached Singleton in 1863. Five years after, an earthquake shook Newcastle and Maitland.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThe railway line was extended from Newcastle to Tamworth in 1878. By 1887, the governor of NSW opened the stream tram line, linking Newcastle and Wallsend / Plattsburg. In 1888, the city of Newcastle was linked to Brisbane by rail. Sydney-Newcastle rail line was completed in 1889. Hunter was visited by devastating floods in 1893. Lake Macquarie was proclaimed as a Shire in 1906 following the proclamation of the village of Cessnock in 1908. By 1944, Maitland became a municipality but experienced severe flooding in 1949.\r\n\r\nElectric trams were eliminated from Newcastle city and suburbs by 1950. By 1952, the Hexham Bridge opened. Queen Elizabeth II and the Duke of Edinburgh visited the Hunter in 1954. After a year, Hunter was met with disastrous floods.\r\n\r\nThe Glenbawn Dam officially opened in 1958 followed by the Grahamstown Dam in 1964. On 14 February in the year of1966, Decimal Currency was introduced. By 1970, Muswellbrook was incorporated as a municipality. The Lostock Dam was built in 1971 and the Stockton Bridge replaced the vehicular ferry service. In 1977, Lake Macquarie was proclaimed a municipality, and then proclaimed a city by 1984.\r\n\r\nIn 2002, the Fernleigh Track was opened. The master plan for a civic cultural precinct in the heart of the Newcastle CBD was launched in 2003. To secure the water future of the Lower Hunter and the Central Coast regions for at least 60 years, the State Government announced the Tillegra Dam plan in 2006. In June 8 of 2007, flooding occurred on Nobbys Beach from a storm that strands bulk carrier Pasha Bulker on the beach and caused a widespread damage in the Hunter.\r\n<h3>History of Newcastle</h3>\r\nIt was the Awabakal people who lived in the Newcastle area for countless generations. They know Newcastle as Muloobinba, which means ‘place of edible sea fern’.\r\n<h4>Settlement of Newcastle</h4>\r\nIt was Lieutenant Shortland who discovered the place, explored it and named it. Newcastle has chosen the landing of the lieutenant at Signal Hill and Stockton on September 9, 1797 as the founding of the city. Newcastle is the area of the second European settlement in Australia. Before the discovery Lieutenant Shortland, on May 10, 1770, as Captain Cook sailed north, he marked on a map the rocky islet of Nobby’s Head at its mouth.\r\n\r\nThe abundance of coal in the area was reported by Lieutenant Shortland, having the first shipment of coal sent to Bengal afterwards in 1799. Thus, Newcastle was Australia’s first commercial port.\r\n\r\nHowever, the first settlement was short lived. There was a mutiny and closing in early 1802 after the believed to be the first coal mine in the Southern Hemisphere at Colliers Point sank.\r\n\r\nAfterwards, a new settlement was established in 1804. Newcastle was made as a place of secondary punishment for unruly convicts and was renamed after England’s famous coal port, Newcastle. On the 10 March 1804, the new settlement arrived at the Hunter River under the appointment of Superintendent Lieutenant Charles Menzies.\r\n\r\nThe streets of Newcastle were laid out by Captain James Wallis. He also built the first church, which was on the site of the present Christ Church Cathedral, and erected the old gaol on the seashore. The breakwater, which now joins Nobby’s to the mainland, was also began by him. However, the quality of these buildings was poor. Only the much-reinforced breakwall managed to survive. A public school was built in east Newcastle in 1861. It was Newcastle East Public School, and it was for the children of soldiers and convicts. The school became Australia’s oldest school.\r\n\r\nPenal settlement on Newcastle remained until 1822, when the settlement was opened up to farming. In 1823, the military rule ended and the prisoner numbers were reduced to 100.\r\n\r\n<strong>Civilian Government</strong>\r\n\r\nIn 1823, the town was finally freed from the infamous influence of the penal law after the removal of the last convicts. The town began to obtain the aspect of an Australian pioneer settlement having a steady flow of free settlers.\r\n\r\n<strong>World War II</strong>\r\n\r\nNewcastle served as an important industrial centre for the Australian war effort during the Second World War. Newcastle was considered to be potentially targeted by the Japanese at that time.\r\n\r\nIn 1942, Newcastle was briefly shelled by the Japanese submarine. The dockyards, the steel works, the breakwall and Art Deco ocean baths were among the areas that were hit. Fortunately, there were no casualties in the attack.\r\n\r\n<strong>Disasters</strong>\r\n\r\nThere was an earthquake on December 28, 1989 in Newcastle. Measuring 5.6 on the Richter scale, the earthquake killed 13 people, injured 162 and damaged a number of prominent buildings. The earthquake took the city several years to recover.\r\n\r\nHunter Region and the Central Coast were damaged by the worst series of storms to hit NSW in 30 years. Extensive flooding and nine deaths were the results of the storms. Many homes were flooded and destroyed.\r\n\r\n<strong>Maritime</strong>\r\n\r\nOn 1934, the Stockton-bound ferry <em>Bluebell </em>sank in the middle of the Hunter River when it collided with the coastal freighter, <em>Waraneen</em>. The collision claimed three lives and caused to admit fifteen passengers to the hospital. Although it was the most tragic maritime accident of the twentieth-century in Newcastle, Newcastle has a very long history of shipwrecks.\r\n\r\n<strong>Aviation</strong>\r\n\r\nA RAAF F-86 Sabre crashed into the suburb of The Junction on 1966 when the pilot, Flying Officer Warren William Goddard, had engine troubles and unsuccessfully tried to fly the plane out to the Pacific Ocean. The pilot was killed when his parachute failed and crashed through the roof of a house. Nobody was killed or injured by the aircraft wreckage. A memorial plaque was unveiled for the killed pilot on 2007.\r\n\r\n<strong>Modern Times</strong>\r\n\r\nIn Australia, Newcastle is the oldest and second largest tonnage throughput port. As the world’s largest coal export port, over 3,000 shipping movements handling cargo of 93,000,000 tonnes (92,000,000 long tons; 103,000,000 short tons) per annum, of which coal exports represented 88,880,000 tonnes (87,480,000 long tons; 97,970,000 short tons) in 2007 / 2008. Thus, the port of Newcastle still remains the economic and trade centre for the resource rick Hunter Valley. Environmental groups are opposed by the volume of coal exported and the attempts to increase the coal exports.\r\n\r\nIn 1999, the steel works closed, making the era of extensive industry pass. Still, there are plenty of the remaining manufacturing industries located away from the city.\r\n\r\nAlthough there are some new apartments and hotels built in recent years in the old city centre, the rate of commercial and retail occupation remains low while the alternate suburban centres have become more significant. The Honeysuckle harbor, a major urban renewal area, is where the CBD is shifting to. This project is to ensure that the shift of businesses and residents to the suburbs is held.\r\n\r\nThere are a number of historic buildings located at Newcastle’s eastern end, which was the old central business district. Among the historic buildings are the Art Deco University House, the Longworth Institute, the City hall, the old Customs House, and Fort Scratchley. The residents of Newcastle call themselves as “Novocastrians”.\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>','History','','inherit','open','closed','','637-revision-13','','','2012-10-20 04:23:14','2012-10-19 19:23:14','',637,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/archives/656',0,'revision','',0),(657,1,'2012-10-20 04:23:56','2012-10-19 19:23:56','<h3>Newcastle and Hunter Region<strong></strong></h3>\r\nThe first record in history of the Hunter Region happened in the city of Newcastle with the recording from Captain Cook of the Nobbys during the 1770. Before the years of 1797, it was the Awabakal, Worimi, Wonnarua, Geawegal, Birrpai and Darkinung Aboriginal tribes which inhabited the area now called a Hunter Region. In 1797, the Hunter River was named by Lt. John Shortland when he discovered it and reported coal outcrops. The first coal exported from the Hunter happened during 1799.\r\n\r\nBy 1800, the entrance to Lake Macquarie was discovered by William Reid, mistaking it for Newcastle Heads. It was in 1801 when a penal colony was established for the first time. Within 12 months, it was abandoned after convict mutiny. Hunter exported its first cedar cut. The second attempt at penal colony was successful in 1804. In 1818, the breakwater to join Nobbys island to the shore was started, ordered by Governr Macquarie to create the port.\r\n\r\nDisastrous Hunter floods came in 1819. By 1822, 