England’s famous coal port, Newcastle. On the 10 March 1804, the new settlement arrived at the Hunter River under the appointment of Superintendent Lieutenant Charles Menzies.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The streets of Newcastle were laid out by Captain James Wallis. He also built the first church, which was on the site of the present Christ Church Cathedral, and erected the old gaol on the seashore. The breakwater, which now joins Nobby’s to the mainland, was also began by him. However, the quality of these buildings was poor. Only the much-reinforced breakwall managed to survive. A public school was built in east Newcastle in 1861. It was Newcastle East Public School, and it was for the children of soldiers and convicts. The school became Australia’s oldest school.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Penal settlement on Newcastle remained until 1822, when the settlement was opened up to farming. In 1823, the military rule ended and the prisoner numbers were reduced to 100.</p>\r\n<strong>Civilian Government</strong>\r\n\r\nIn 1823, the town was finally freed from the infamous influence of the penal law after the removal of the last convicts. The town began to obtain the aspect of an Australian pioneer settlement having a steady flow of free settlers.\r\n\r\n<strong>World War II</strong>\r\n\r\nNewcastle served as an important industrial centre for the Australian war effort during the Second World War. Newcastle was considered to be potentially targeted by the Japanese at that time.\r\n\r\nIn 1942, Newcastle was briefly shelled by the Japanese submarine. The dockyards, the steel works, the breakwall and Art Deco ocean baths were among the areas that were hit. Fortunately, there were no casualties in the attack.\r\n\r\n<strong>Disasters</strong>\r\n\r\nThere was an earthquake on December 28, 1989 in Newcastle. Measuring 5.6 on the Richter scale, the earthquake killed 13 people, injured 162 and damaged a number of prominent buildings. The earthquake took the city several years to recover.\r\n\r\nHunter Region and the Central Coast were damaged by the worst series of storms to hit NSW in 30 years. Extensive flooding and nine deaths were the results of the storms. Many homes were flooded and destroyed.\r\n\r\n<strong>Maritime</strong>\r\n\r\nOn 1934, the Stockton-bound ferry <em>Bluebell </em>sank in the middle of the Hunter River when it collided with the coastal freighter, <em>Waraneen</em>. The collision claimed three lives and caused to admit fifteen passengers to the hospital. Although it was the most tragic maritime accident of the twentieth-century in Newcastle, Newcastle has a very long history of shipwrecks.\r\n\r\n<strong>Aviation</strong>\r\n\r\nA RAAF F-86 Sabre crashed into the suburb of The Junction on 1966 when the pilot, Flying Officer Warren William Goddard, had engine troubles and unsuccessfully tried to fly the plane out to the Pacific Ocean. The pilot was killed when his parachute failed and crashed through the roof of a house. Nobody was killed or injured by the aircraft wreckage. A memorial plaque was unveiled for the killed pilot on 2007.\r\n\r\n<strong>Modern Times</strong>\r\n\r\nIn Australia, Newcastle is the oldest and second largest tonnage throughput port. As the world’s largest coal export port, over 3,000 shipping movements handling cargo of 93,000,000 tonnes (92,000,000 long tons; 103,000,000 short tons) per annum, of which coal exports represented 88,880,000 tonnes (87,480,000 long tons; 97,970,000 short tons) in 2007 / 2008. Thus, the port of Newcastle still remains the economic and trade centre for the resource rick Hunter Valley. Environmental groups are opposed by the volume of coal exported and the attempts to increase the coal exports.\r\n\r\nIn 1999, the steel works closed, making the era of extensive industry pass. Still, there are plenty of the remaining manufacturing industries located away from the city.\r\n\r\nAlthough there are some new apartments and hotels built in recent years in the old city centre, the rate of commercial and retail occupation remains low while the alternate suburban centres have become more significant. The Honeysuckle harbor, a major urban renewal area, is where the CBD is shifting to. This project is to ensure that the shift of businesses and residents to the suburbs is held.\r\n\r\nThere are a number of historic buildings located at Newcastle’s eastern end, which was the old central business district. Among the historic buildings are the Art Deco University House, the Longworth Institute, the City hall, the old Customs House, and Fort Scratchley. The residents of Newcastle call themselves as “Novocastrians”.\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>','History','','inherit','open','closed','','637-revision-14','','','2012-10-20 04:23:56','2012-10-19 19:23:56','',637,'http://localhost/aus-newcastle/archives/657',0,'revision','',0),(658,1,'2012-10-20 04:28:35','2012-10-19 19:28:35','Located approximately 160 kilometres north of Sydney, the Hunter Region has a population of 658608. Most of the population lives in the cities of Newcastle and Lake Macquarie.\r\n\r\nThe Hunter Region contains the Hunter River and its tributaries wit highland areas. One of the largest river valleys on the NSW coast is the Hunter Valley.\r\n<h3>Hunter Region Local Government Areas<strong> </strong></h3>\r\nThere are eleven main local government areas within the Hunter Region - Cessnock, Dungog, Gloucester, Great Lakes, Lake Macquarie, Maitland, Muswellbrook, Newcastle, Port Stephens, Singleton and Upper Hunter.\r\n\r\nBelow is the list of LGAs in the Hunter Region with their descriptions, suburbs or towns and prospective post codes and house median price included.\r\n\r\nFor the house median price, some amounts are recorded over the past year/s. The year already stated beside the amount for your own convenience. Present year house median prices have no year placed beside them. <em>E.g. $462,500 (2011)</em>\r\n<h4>Cessnock<strong> </strong></h4